# Add a GUIDED-INQUIRY flow to a sim

You are authoring the guided-inquiry stepper for ONE simulation that is **already on
the global shell** (it has `#aside-inquiry`, `#inq-cards`, and a `Shell` runtime that
owns the dots, Next/Finish, Skip, restore, and ‹ › pager). You write **only** the step
cards, the per-step scene evolution (`onStep`), and the prediction-feedback handler.
Never build the dots/Next/Skip/pager — the shell does. Never touch physics or rendering.

## Reference (read first)
- `_design-reference/SHELL-DESIGN-GUIDE.md` §6 — card markup, gating, feedback handler, CSS.
- `_design-reference/reference-converted-sim.html` — copy exact card/handler markup when unsure.

## The one principle: expose the sim in dependency order
Sequence the cards so the student meets ideas in the order the physics depends on them.
**Establish each prerequisite — and drive the sim to show it — before the concept that
builds on it.** Never reveal the payoff before its groundwork.

> **Example — total internal reflection.** Correct order:
> 1. Ground the setup: light passing dense → less-dense medium, refracting away from the
>    normal at a small angle (baseline: Snell / refraction).
> 2. Predict: as the incidence angle grows, what does the refracted ray do? → observe it
>    bend toward the surface, approaching 90°.
> 3. **Critical angle FIRST:** define θc as the angle where the refracted ray reaches
>    exactly 90°; predict its value, then drive the sim there and confirm.
> 4. **Only now TIR:** predict what happens *beyond* θc (wrong-choice misconception: "it
>    keeps refracting" / "it vanishes") → observe total internal reflection.
> 5. Resolve: the takeaway + the condition (θ > θc, n₁ > n₂).
>
> Critical angle is the boundary that *defines* TIR, so it must be understood and seen
> before TIR appears. Apply this dependency-ordering to any sim.

## The arc (4–6 cards)
Ground/orient → predict (gated) → observe/verify → introduce next layer (predict first)
→ observe payoff → resolve. One new idea per card. Each card's prose ties to what the
sim is showing *at that step*.

## The scene must follow the cards (`onStep(i)`)
This is what makes it "step by step." In the SIM JS, implement `onStep(i)` to drive the
simulation into the exact state that card i discusses — set the relevant parameter,
reveal/hide a layer, pause on a predict card, highlight the quantity in play.
- Make `onStep(i)` **deterministic and self-contained** — it fully sets the state for
  step i (don't rely on the previous step). This way the ‹ › pager and revisits restore
  each card's scene intact.
- Read `Shell.step` in your draw code where the visuals differ per step.
- Example (TIR): step 2 → `angle = θc - 8°`; step 3 → `angle = θc`; step 4 → `angle = θc + 12°`.
- The sim stays fully usable throughout — inquiry gates only its own Next, never the sim.

## Card markup (fill `#inq-cards`)
    <!-- Gated predict: Next waits until a choice is picked -->
    <div class="inq-step" data-gate>
      <h4>3 · Predict the critical angle</h4>
      <p>Question tied to the current scene…</p>
      <button class="choice" data-correct="0" data-fb="Rebuttal, shown only if picked…">A) misconception</button>
      <button class="choice" data-correct="1" data-fb="Why it's right — <strong>the key fact</strong>.">B) correct</button>
      <div class="predict-eval"></div>
    </div>

    <!-- Ungated observe: Next enabled immediately -->
    <div class="inq-step">
      <h4>4 · Watch total internal reflection</h4>
      <p>Press ▶ / drag the angle past θc and watch…</p>
    </div>

- `data-gate` on any card whose Next should wait for an answer (shell enables Next on the
  first `.choice` click; for a "watch it first" gate, call `Shell.stepReady()` when done).
- **Encode the misconception as a wrong `.choice`** with its rebuttal in `data-fb`.
  **Never** write a standing "common misconception" text card — it teaches the error.
- Keep prose ≥ 14px, a few sentences; the canvas shows, the card explains.

## Prediction-feedback handler + CSS (add once to the SIM JS / SIM CSS)
    document.querySelectorAll('#inq-cards .inq-step').forEach(card=>{
      const evalBox=card.querySelector('.predict-eval');
      const choices=card.querySelectorAll('.choice');
      choices.forEach(ch=>ch.addEventListener('click',()=>{
        if(card.dataset.answered) return; card.dataset.answered='1';
        const correct=ch.dataset.correct==='1';
        choices.forEach(c=>{ c.disabled=true;
          if(c.dataset.correct==='1') c.classList.add('correct');
          else if(c===ch) c.classList.add('wrong'); else c.classList.add('dim'); });
        if(evalBox){ evalBox.innerHTML=ch.dataset.fb||''; evalBox.classList.add('show', correct?'correct':'wrong'); }
      }));
    });

    .inq-step h4{margin:0 0 8px;font-size:14px;font-weight:600;color:var(--text);}
    .inq-step p{margin:0 0 12px;font-size:14px;line-height:1.55;color:var(--muted);}
    .inq-step .predict-eval{display:none;} .inq-step .predict-eval.show{display:block;}

## Do NOT
- Change physics, equations, or rendering; add/remove sim controls; rename shell IDs.
- Build dots/Next/Finish/Skip/pager, or gate the simulation itself.
- Reveal a concept before its prerequisite; stack two new ideas in one card; write a
  standing-misconception card.

## Self-check
- [ ] 4–6 cards in dependency order; each prerequisite shown before what depends on it.
- [ ] Every predict card is `data-gate` with a wrong-choice misconception + `data-fb`
      and a `.predict-eval`; the feedback handler + CSS are present.
- [ ] `onStep(i)` deterministically drives the scene for each card; ‹ › back/forward
      restores each card's state; the sim is usable from load.
- [ ] Physics/render code unchanged; no console errors.
